# TypeScript Modules and Namespaces

TypeScript's module system sits on top of JavaScript's ES module standard. The mental model: each file with `import` or `export` is a **module** — an isolated namespace. Files without those keywords are **global scripts** — variables leak into the global scope.

```
Module vs Script distinction:

math.ts (script — NO import/export)
  const PI = 3.14;        ← leaks to global scope
  function add() {}       ← leaks to global scope

math.ts (module — HAS import/export)
  export const PI = 3.14; ← private to this file unless exported
  const add = () => {};   ← private, not exported

  Other files CANNOT access PI until they explicitly:
  import { PI } from './math';
```

## ES Module Syntax

```ts
// Named exports — explicit names, importers use exact names or alias
export const PI = 3.14;
export function add(a: number, b: number): number { return a + b; }
export type { UserId };  // type-only export (erased in JS output)

// Default export — one per file, importers choose their own name
export default class Calculator { /* ... */ }

// Re-export from another module:
export { add, PI } from './math';
export * from './utils';  // re-export everything
export * as utils from './utils';  // namespace re-export
```

```ts
// Named import
import { add, PI } from './math';
import { add as sum, PI as circlePI } from './math';  // aliases

// Default import
import Calculator from './calculator';  // any name works

// Namespace import — all exports become properties on a single object
import * as math from './math';
math.add(1, 2);
math.PI;

// Type-only import — erased entirely at compile time (no runtime import)
import type { User } from './types';
```

## CommonJS Interop

```ts
// CJS requires go through the interop layer:
import path from 'path';           // default import of CJS module
import { join } from 'path';       // named import (TS synthesizes .join)
import * as fs from 'fs';          // namespace import

// esModuleInterop: true (default in newer projects) enables clean syntax
// Without it, CJS defaults must be imported as:
import path = require('path');     // TS namespace import syntax

// The crucial difference:
// CJS: module.exports = { join, ... }      (exports is an object)
// ESM: export function join() {}           (named export)
// TypeScript bridges them via synthetic default exports
```

## Module Resolution — how TypeScript finds files

```
Two resolution strategies:

1. node (legacy) / node16 (modern)
   import { x } from './utils';
   TS looks for:
     ./utils.ts
     ./utils.tsx
     ./utils/index.ts
     ./utils.d.ts

2. bundler (Vite/webpack projects)
   Respects paths config, supports ESM
   Allows extensionless imports

Barespecifier (no ./ or /) resolution:
   import { x } from 'lodash';
   TS looks in:
     node_modules/lodash/index.d.ts
     node_modules/@types/lodash/index.d.ts
```

## Path Aliases — tsconfig paths

```json
// tsconfig.json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "baseUrl": ".",
    "paths": {
      "@/*": ["src/*"],
      "@components/*": ["src/components/*"]
    }
  }
}
```

```ts
// Before: deep relative imports
import { Button } from '../../../../components/Button';

// After: alias import
import { Button } from '@components/Button';
```

> **⚠️ Note:** `paths` in tsconfig is for TypeScript checking ONLY. Bundlers (Vite, webpack) need their own alias config pointing to the same directories.

## Namespaces (internal modules)

```ts
// Namespace — wrap related code in a named scope
// Used primarily in .d.ts files and legacy code
namespace Validation {
  export interface Validator {
    isValid(s: string): boolean;
  }

  export class EmailValidator implements Validator {
    isValid(s: string) { return s.includes('@'); }
  }
}

const v = new Validation.EmailValidator();
v.isValid('test@example.com');

// Modern code prefers ES modules over namespaces
// Namespaces compile to IIFEs with a shared object:
// (function(Validation) {
//   Validation.EmailValidator = ...
// })(Validation || (Validation = {}));
```

## Ambient Declarations — `.d.ts` files

Ambient declarations describe the shape of code that exists at runtime but wasn't written in TypeScript:

```ts
// custom.d.ts — tells TypeScript about a global variable injected by the HTML page
declare const __APP_VERSION__: string;
declare const __BUILD_DATE__: number;

// Tell TS to treat SVG imports as React components:
declare module '*.svg' {
  import React from 'react';
  const ReactComponent: React.FunctionComponent<React.SVGProps<SVGSVGElement>>;
  export default ReactComponent;
}

// Extend an existing module:
declare module 'express' {
  interface Request {
    user?: { id: string; role: string };
  }
}
// Now req.user is typed everywhere in Express routes
```

## Module System Cheatsheet

| Feature | Syntax | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Named export | `export const x = ...` | Explicit name |
| Default export | `export default ...` | One per file |
| Type-only export | `export type { T }` | Erased in output |
| Type-only import | `import type { T }` | Zero JS output |
| Re-export | `export { x } from './y'` | Passthrough |
| Namespace import | `import * as ns from './y'` | All exports as object |
| Path alias | `@/*` in tsconfig paths | TypeScript only |
| Ambient module | `declare module 'x' {}` | For untyped packages |

## Common Pitfalls
- Adding `import/export` to a file to make it a module — sometimes you want a global script for declaration files
- `import type` is not just a hint — it catches cases where a value import would create a circular dependency
- `paths` in tsconfig does NOT configure your bundler — both need configuration
- Circular imports: two modules importing each other can lead to `undefined` at runtime in CJS; ESM handles it better via live bindings
- `esModuleInterop: true` is required for clean default imports from CJS packages like lodash, express

